WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Our next speaker is a new friend of mine, and I'm happy to introduce, please join me

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:47.680
Hello, and welcome to San Francisco.

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:51.320
I'm so excited to be here speaking at RStudio conference.

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:55.599
I'll explain a little bit about my background.

00:00:55.599 --> 00:01:05.379
But this is one of my favorite conferences, definitely top two in San Francisco.

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:10.599
But I'm excited to be here, excited to talk to you about growth hacking with R and different

00:01:10.599 --> 00:01:11.599
analytics.

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:17.160
So with that, if you've ever heard a Salesforce presentation before, you know what's coming

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:18.160
next.

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:20.019
And that's the forward looking statement.

00:01:20.019 --> 00:01:23.360
So I'm not really going to talk about Salesforce software today.

00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:30.040
However, if you are considering buying Salesforce, please make sure that you consider only features

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:31.959
that are regularly available in the market.

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:35.199
Okay, now that's out of the way, I'm going to give you a little bit of an introduction

00:01:35.199 --> 00:01:37.440
for myself a little bit of a personal background.

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:44.639
I studied undergrad at UPenn, economics and film studies, so left brain, right brain.

00:01:44.639 --> 00:01:51.919
And when I graduated, I went into a career that was hiring, I graduated in the recession.

00:01:51.919 --> 00:01:56.800
And I spent the first 10 years of my career at Macy's doing merchandising.

00:01:56.800 --> 00:02:01.519
And you know, it, it was a great company to learn business.

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:05.279
It was in transition, there was a data transition happening.

00:02:05.279 --> 00:02:10.259
But I didn't quite feel the right fit professionally.

00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:14.919
And I was looking for somewhere to go looking how to transition.

00:02:14.919 --> 00:02:16.119
And it was very difficult.

00:02:16.119 --> 00:02:19.880
You know, we had a statistics department, but they were all PhDs.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:21.839
And fortunately, the world changed.

00:02:21.839 --> 00:02:30.279
And right at this point, this little red line, I discovered R. And it was this community

00:02:30.279 --> 00:02:37.259
that's helped each other, that's educated, that's helped me transform not only my career,

00:02:37.259 --> 00:02:40.720
but my life, my family.

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:45.399
It took me to a master's in analytics from NYU, I relocated from the East Coast to the

00:02:45.399 --> 00:02:48.839
West Coast, and worked in e commerce grocery.

00:02:48.839 --> 00:02:54.479
And then most recently, now at Salesforce doing software analytics, product analytics

00:02:54.479 --> 00:02:56.020
and data science.

00:02:56.020 --> 00:03:00.360
And so really, the thing that I need to say, more than anything, is thank you, thank you

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:04.440
to this community, you've helped me in ways that you can't really know.

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:08.240
And I really, truly appreciate that, which is why I'm so excited to hear to talk to you

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:12.399
about my topic, and hopefully give back a little bit.

00:03:12.399 --> 00:03:15.940
So before we get started, I'll just talk real quickly, what is Salesforce?

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:19.699
If you're in San Francisco, and you ask different people, you'll say, what is Salesforce?

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:21.960
Most people say it's a tower.

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:24.460
Some people will say it's a transit center.

00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:27.500
But really, what is it?

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:32.080
Salesforce brings customers and companies together.

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:34.380
And that's really what our mission is.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:39.179
And how we do that is through a suite of cloud software products.

00:03:39.179 --> 00:03:42.460
If you work in sales, you're very familiar with sales cloud.

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:49.699
But service cloud powers customer call centers and customer service.

00:03:49.699 --> 00:03:55.419
Marketing cloud touches almost everybody here through targeted marketing, emails, push notifications.

00:03:55.419 --> 00:03:56.820
Commerce cloud runs e commerce websites.

00:03:56.820 --> 00:04:01.940
So there's a whole suite of cloud based applications.

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:07.059
Most recently in the analytics cloud for us is Tableau, which is a recent acquisition.

00:04:07.059 --> 00:04:12.699
And like that, we have a platform of technologies and emerging technologies that are built right

00:04:12.699 --> 00:04:13.860
into Salesforce.

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:19.000
So mobile, blockchain, artificial intelligence with our Einstein.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:20.940
So this is what Salesforce is.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:25.660
It is a big company with petabytes of data.

00:04:25.660 --> 00:04:27.940
And who deals with the data?

00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:30.579
And that would be the data intelligence team at Salesforce.

00:04:30.579 --> 00:04:32.500
And that's the team that I work on.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:40.299
Our team is divided into five pillars of the modern challenges of data at a company.

00:04:40.299 --> 00:04:44.859
But what I'll talk to for myself, most important, is strategy and growth.

00:04:44.859 --> 00:04:48.500
And that leads into this talk.

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:56.779
So the customer journey, particularly for SaaS companies, deals with acquisition, retention,

00:04:56.779 --> 00:05:00.220
keeping the customer, and then cross selling and upselling.

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:09.339
And so this customer journey has a lot of support behind it in steps one and three.

00:05:09.339 --> 00:05:15.339
And primarily, acquiring new customers is very robust with marketing attribution analysis

00:05:15.339 --> 00:05:19.220
and a lot of marketing analytics that is very well codified.

00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:21.899
And the same thing with the last step with cross selling.

00:05:21.899 --> 00:05:27.179
Market basket analysis, a priori algorithm, there's books about it, they teach it in school.

00:05:27.179 --> 00:05:29.459
And so it's something that's fairly common.

00:05:29.459 --> 00:05:36.260
But retention analytics, I found, and particularly when we're doing hiring, is a lot less structured

00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:40.179
and a lot less organized in an academic sense.

00:05:40.179 --> 00:05:45.380
And so what is that middle piece?

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:50.779
And so what I'm calling it today, growth hacking, but also growth analytics and retention analytics,

00:05:50.779 --> 00:05:52.220
is focusing on the customers that you have.

00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:57.619
So not worrying about cross selling or acquisition, but focusing on how to keep users, how to

00:05:57.619 --> 00:05:58.739
keep customers.

00:05:58.739 --> 00:06:05.019
And we have some primary metrics that are very important to growth analytics and retention

00:06:05.019 --> 00:06:06.579
analytics.

00:06:06.579 --> 00:06:08.059
The big one is MAL.

00:06:08.059 --> 00:06:12.220
And what's different from software from other businesses, and you can see this when you

00:06:12.220 --> 00:06:15.899
read it in the news, is that they don't talk about sales.

00:06:15.899 --> 00:06:18.779
They don't talk about clicks or purchases or items.

00:06:18.779 --> 00:06:23.179
If you read about Slack versus Microsoft Teams or things like that, they talk about users

00:06:23.179 --> 00:06:24.579
and active users.

00:06:24.579 --> 00:06:29.500
And that's the primary metric that we focus on, really targeting in and zeroing on that.

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:35.859
Growth analytics is related to LTV and LTV analysis, but it differs in some key ways.

00:06:35.859 --> 00:06:38.220
And I'll show kind of an example of that.

00:06:38.220 --> 00:06:42.100
And really, the interesting thing about this analysis, it's fairly simple.

00:06:42.100 --> 00:06:47.380
But the key is to finding different segments and cohorts within the data to find differences

00:06:47.380 --> 00:06:48.380
between that.

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:52.059
And I'll show how to do that with this talk.

00:06:52.059 --> 00:06:55.420
So we're going to focus today mostly on MAL and retention.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:58.540
But there's a lot of challenges with retention analytics.

00:06:58.540 --> 00:07:01.179
And the challenge is that we tend to use log data.

00:07:01.179 --> 00:07:03.299
So we use instrumented data on logs.

00:07:03.299 --> 00:07:06.739
It could be logs from a website, logs within software.

00:07:06.739 --> 00:07:07.739
But it's machine logs.

00:07:07.739 --> 00:07:09.420
This is mostly for engineers.

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:12.339
This isn't optimized for analytics.

00:07:12.339 --> 00:07:13.339
But they're abundant.

00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:17.339
There's, like I said, petabytes of data that you can use.

00:07:17.339 --> 00:07:20.220
It's just it's really hard to use because it could be redundant.

00:07:20.380 --> 00:07:22.260
There could be many challenges with it.

00:07:22.260 --> 00:07:24.220
And it requires a lot of transformation.

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:26.059
And there are commercial tools available.

00:07:26.059 --> 00:07:29.339
However, they are very expensive.

00:07:29.339 --> 00:07:30.339
And this is our studio.

00:07:30.339 --> 00:07:31.339
This is our conference.

00:07:31.339 --> 00:07:33.899
We want it to be free and open source.

00:07:33.899 --> 00:07:37.660
And the challenge that I find and what I see is that there's a skills gap in taking those

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:42.000
raw logs and converting it to an action and an insight.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:46.220
And so what I'm going to show here is using the tidyverse syntax, generating product analytics

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:48.579
KPIs with very little code.

00:07:48.579 --> 00:07:53.980
So if you were looking for something using PCA and something really complex, I apologize.

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:59.140
This is going to be very, very concise and hopefully very usable.

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:01.220
Retention analytics in R. All right.

00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:03.500
So we're going to use four main packages today.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:06.500
Obviously, the tidyverse.

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:11.140
We're going to use Plotly, Formatable, which is based off of Knitter, and then HTML widgets.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:18.540
The data that we're going to use is all generated, is random, is not any user data from Salesforce.

00:08:19.500 --> 00:08:24.579
But that data set is something that I will release about how to generate it so you, too,

00:08:24.579 --> 00:08:25.579
can do this.

00:08:25.579 --> 00:08:29.100
And so when we look at the data, what we see is we see it's at the month grain.

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:30.220
We have a user ID.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:32.859
So we have user logs per month.

00:08:32.859 --> 00:08:36.380
And then we have some, let's call it demographic data behind it.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:41.260
So maybe what industry this user is in, what region.

00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:44.940
And we'll show you how to slice that on cohorts.

00:08:44.940 --> 00:08:49.739
Now, what's really interesting, when you think about retention analytics and the key

00:08:49.739 --> 00:08:57.140
KPI of MAU, R does not have in its base diff time function monthly units.

00:08:57.140 --> 00:08:59.140
It stops at weeks.

00:08:59.140 --> 00:09:01.940
And this was really interesting because you could be kind of working through this and

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:03.260
say, why isn't it working a month?

00:09:03.260 --> 00:09:04.260
What's wrong with my code?

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:08.179
Why am I calculating month in millisecond intervals?

00:09:08.179 --> 00:09:12.340
And so to get around that, this was actually the R community that posted this on Stack

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:16.700
Overflow as a custom function to do monthly intervals.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:20.979
And so we're going to rely on that with some other functions.

00:09:20.979 --> 00:09:22.840
OK.

00:09:22.840 --> 00:09:30.780
We take that raw data set of logs and using really two lines, we mutate it very easily

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.820
to get the most important piece of information for retention analytics.

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:38.940
So we're going to group by the user ID, and then we're going to mutate and we're going

00:09:38.940 --> 00:09:42.940
to add an age and the first month, the start month.

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:45.580
And this start month is when we first see that user.

00:09:45.580 --> 00:09:47.140
That's time zero.

00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:49.299
You'll see why that's important.

00:09:49.299 --> 00:09:52.460
And because we use mutate, we use custom functions, it's very easy.

00:09:52.460 --> 00:09:56.140
We're just going to use this elapsed month function.

00:09:56.140 --> 00:09:58.059
OK.

00:09:58.059 --> 00:10:00.780
This is the retention code.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:05.500
This is what will generate all of our visualizations, all of our analysis.

00:10:05.500 --> 00:10:10.380
And I apologize if you were looking for PCA or hyperplanes or multi-dimension.

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:11.380
It is very easy.

00:10:11.380 --> 00:10:12.979
It is only three lines.

00:10:12.979 --> 00:10:17.419
Once we have that age data, we're going to group it by that age, we're going to summarize

00:10:17.419 --> 00:10:22.099
it by looking at a total users over time, and then we're going to mutate what this retention

00:10:22.099 --> 00:10:23.500
percentage is.

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:29.260
So this, what we see, is that we have 13,000 users to start with in our total data set,

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:35.320
13,000 users that initially start, and then over time, you see them falling off.

00:10:36.140 --> 00:10:39.059
And this is very good for somebody to just sort of see in a table, but it doesn't really

00:10:39.059 --> 00:10:40.280
make sense.

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:43.880
And so what we do then is we show it in a ggplot.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:48.760
And what this table shows, what this chart shows on the x-axis, is sort of that age,

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:49.880
that life.

00:10:49.880 --> 00:10:53.679
What is that life of the user, and how many users do you retain over time?

00:10:53.679 --> 00:10:59.080
And what's important for software is that if your user base goes to zero after a certain

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:03.520
amount of time, you probably have some problems with your product, or you have a certain product

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:05.960
that needs a certain fit, you need to keep releasing new things.

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:10.599
But for this, if you're in software, if you're in SaaS business like this, and you go towards

00:11:10.599 --> 00:11:14.320
zero, something's wrong, you need to see that.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:16.760
And this is the base function that we look at.

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:21.799
But what's more important is the analysis and finding those different cohorts.

00:11:21.799 --> 00:11:27.000
And so just by changing that one line, by changing that group by function, and by adding

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.479
a color, all of a sudden you have something much more useful and much more insightful.

00:11:31.479 --> 00:11:33.960
So what are the differences between my users?

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:36.000
Where are they coming from?

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.280
Why is the retention different between the two?

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:39.280
And you can see it.

00:11:39.280 --> 00:11:43.719
Somebody can understand, in this case, maybe how the banking industry is outperforming

00:11:43.719 --> 00:11:46.200
the tech industry for user retention.

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:49.880
And that leads to business insights and then strategies.

00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:53.559
Now this is useful, but it's also hard to read.

00:11:53.559 --> 00:11:58.000
If you look at it, you can say, well, at 10 months, what's the overall difference between

00:11:58.000 --> 00:11:59.500
the two groups?

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:02.380
You can kind of parse it out, but not so great.

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:04.020
And that's where we use Plotly.

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:06.900
And again, I apologize how simple it is.

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:12.739
You take that ggplot that we did in the last chart that we saved, a ggchart variable, and

00:12:12.739 --> 00:12:15.900
all you do is you just put it into ggplotly.

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:19.500
And because of the community that's coded this, the work is done, and you can see very

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:24.340
easily, an end user can see, the differences between the groups in a visual form.

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:29.700
And they can really see and understand what's going on with their user base.

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:36.020
Now R, being the fantastic tool that it is, can handle much more complexity than that.

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:38.900
And so one of the things that we look at is we can look at change over time.

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:43.460
And the change over time can be represented by this starting of the different cohorts.

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:48.700
And what we see in this chart is that we have two years of data.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:53.799
And while it looks like spaghetti, based on the coloring schemes that R just did right

00:12:53.799 --> 00:13:00.599
out of the box, changing that date to a factor, you're able to see what's really going on

00:13:00.599 --> 00:13:02.400
within your user cohorts.

00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:06.440
And this could lead to some useful insights for either seasonality or differences between

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:09.200
customers and user groups.

00:13:09.200 --> 00:13:11.559
Great.

00:13:11.559 --> 00:13:17.320
What we're going to move to from a visual form, and those retention curves look great

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:19.960
on charts, but sometimes you need to go deeper.

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:24.960
Sometimes you need a little bit more insights about granularity, about when something happened

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:25.960
when.

00:13:25.960 --> 00:13:34.359
So this is where we're going to use the tidyverse to stack different functions to make very

00:13:34.359 --> 00:13:36.119
clean chart outputs.

00:13:36.119 --> 00:13:41.119
And so what we have here is we have that same retention curve that we just saw in a visual

00:13:41.119 --> 00:13:43.599
form, but we're looking at it as a table.

00:13:43.599 --> 00:13:49.520
So that the start month on the left, January 2018, you can follow that diagonal where you

00:13:49.520 --> 00:13:51.280
retain all of your users.

00:13:51.280 --> 00:13:52.280
That's when they start.

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:53.280
So you have 100%.

00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:57.559
And as you go each subsequent column, each subsequent month, you can see how many of

00:13:57.559 --> 00:13:59.760
the customers, how many of the users you retain.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:01.479
And so you can see it falls off.

00:14:01.479 --> 00:14:02.479
But it's hard to read.

00:14:02.479 --> 00:14:03.719
It's hard to follow.

00:14:03.719 --> 00:14:11.039
So what we're going to do is we're going to use the scales package, clean it up a little

00:14:11.039 --> 00:14:12.039
bit.

00:14:12.039 --> 00:14:14.479
We're going to replace the NAs, and we're going to make it easier to read.

00:14:14.479 --> 00:14:15.760
So this is an improvement.

00:14:15.760 --> 00:14:19.599
This is starting to get something that's human readable.

00:14:19.599 --> 00:14:21.840
But we can still do better.

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:23.239
We're going to add a little bit more information.

00:14:23.239 --> 00:14:28.960
And using the tidyverse, we're going to stack a join on top of it to show you the size of

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:30.200
the cohort.

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:33.239
So now what you see, you're packing more and more information in it.

00:14:33.239 --> 00:14:35.880
You're saying, which months are important?

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:37.940
What is my retention over time?

00:14:37.940 --> 00:14:42.119
And now you're starting to add some understanding to it.

00:14:42.119 --> 00:14:43.400
But it's still a little bit hard to read.

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:46.760
It's a lot of numbers.

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:48.679
Maybe your data scientists don't like to read as much.

00:14:48.679 --> 00:14:50.400
Maybe your business partners don't.

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:53.099
So we need to make this a little bit easier to understand.

00:14:53.099 --> 00:14:56.559
And so what we're going to do is we're going to use the formatable package.

00:14:56.559 --> 00:15:00.239
We're going to add a lot of gobbledygook code that I'm going to truncate at the bottom.

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:03.880
But what we're going to do is we're going to format it in something that's much more

00:15:03.880 --> 00:15:04.919
readable.

00:15:04.919 --> 00:15:11.280
And so we create a table like this where you have that retention data, that cohort data,

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:13.880
that cohort size, and you've color-coded.

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:16.799
So now you see over time that things are consistent.

00:15:16.799 --> 00:15:22.119
But you really can see what's going on with your user base so that you can see differences

00:15:22.119 --> 00:15:25.359
and try to uncover what's really going on.

00:15:25.359 --> 00:15:29.520
Again, R can handle a lot of complexity.

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:33.619
And the complexity, fortunately for us, is very easy to handle.

00:15:33.619 --> 00:15:41.099
So by adding, again, just two variables in very simple places, you can add much more

00:15:41.099 --> 00:15:45.859
granularity by looking at the industry over time and what the retention is.

00:15:45.859 --> 00:15:50.580
And so compared to the last chart, you see that this group is outperforming in terms

00:15:50.580 --> 00:15:52.979
of retention, the other group.

00:15:52.979 --> 00:15:58.400
But it's these slices, these splits within the data that you can look at to identify

00:15:58.400 --> 00:16:02.099
differences between users and differences within your product.

00:16:02.099 --> 00:16:05.979
This could be users that take a certain action.

00:16:05.979 --> 00:16:08.940
And that's where things really start to get a little bit interesting.

00:16:08.940 --> 00:16:09.940
Okay.

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:10.940
So we've built this.

00:16:10.940 --> 00:16:11.940
We've built this tool.

00:16:11.940 --> 00:16:14.679
We've built it, again, very, very simply.

00:16:14.679 --> 00:16:16.700
But it's not just for us.

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:20.460
We need to get it in the hands of business partners and make it a little bit easier.

00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:22.539
And you could build it into a Shiny application.

00:16:22.539 --> 00:16:24.520
You could host a Shiny application.

00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:26.500
But sometimes there's an easier way.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:28.820
And sometimes you might not have the infrastructure.

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:32.080
So with HTML widgets, you just save it as a widget.

00:16:32.080 --> 00:16:37.140
And what you get is you get an interactive chart that an end user doesn't need to know

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:40.260
anything about R. They don't need to know anything about what you're doing.

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:43.059
They just need to know the language about how to interpret it.

00:16:43.059 --> 00:16:44.739
And now they can use it.

00:16:44.739 --> 00:16:45.799
So you can generate this.

00:16:45.799 --> 00:16:46.799
You can generate this automatically.

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:48.380
You can host it on a server.

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:55.299
And then even without going through something like using R and a Shiny package, you get

00:16:55.299 --> 00:16:56.679
a table.

00:16:56.679 --> 00:16:59.260
So again, very, very simple code.

00:16:59.260 --> 00:17:04.680
And what I've sort of showed was basically what is retention analytics.

00:17:04.680 --> 00:17:10.239
This is a way to kind of get you primed and started about what this field is about in

00:17:10.239 --> 00:17:12.979
growth hacking and retention.

00:17:12.979 --> 00:17:15.040
But I have a confession to make.

00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:22.959
Because it's not entirely true about the field not really having academic work and being

00:17:22.959 --> 00:17:24.719
codified as much.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:28.439
And I'm going to make a plug for your R meetup groups.

00:17:28.439 --> 00:17:32.640
And so I was talking with the Bay Area R meetup group and I was talking about retention analytics

00:17:32.640 --> 00:17:35.199
and a few other product analytics.

00:17:35.199 --> 00:17:43.319
And they said to me, you know, actually what you're doing is just applied survival analysis.

00:17:43.319 --> 00:17:47.079
And so I was thinking about it and I looked at it and I said, wait a second, that's interesting.

00:17:47.079 --> 00:17:51.640
I talked to a university professor about growth hacking and survival analysis.

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:53.540
And this was new to them.

00:17:53.579 --> 00:17:58.020
And that's when I realized that this R community, bringing different groups together, bringing

00:17:58.020 --> 00:18:01.699
different fields, is really where the cutting edge is.

00:18:01.699 --> 00:18:05.420
And joining all that thing is where there's a lot of creativity.

00:18:05.420 --> 00:18:09.739
And so the survival packages and some survival analysis packages, I'm not going to go into

00:18:09.739 --> 00:18:11.060
detail into this.

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:16.420
But if you look at that Kaplan-Meier curve, that is a retention curve that we look at

00:18:16.420 --> 00:18:17.780
in product analytics.

00:18:17.780 --> 00:18:20.140
And you can see the differences between it.

00:18:20.140 --> 00:18:24.180
What you have is you have a hazard function and a regression analysis on the right.

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:27.699
So looking at that same data in a different way.

00:18:27.699 --> 00:18:32.180
And that's really what engages me so much in the R community is that you take something

00:18:32.180 --> 00:18:37.699
that was over here, you take science that was over there, you bring them closer together

00:18:37.699 --> 00:18:39.540
and we're all better off for it.

00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:42.380
So I'm going to make a plug then.

00:18:42.380 --> 00:18:45.900
If you'd like to learn more about survival analysis and start to think about how you

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:50.699
might apply this to your own growth hack and to your own product analytics, there's

00:18:50.699 --> 00:18:55.739
a fantastic detailed book about applied survival analysis using R.

00:18:55.739 --> 00:18:59.819
But if you want to get started, there's a gentleman at the conference.

00:18:59.819 --> 00:19:03.380
I'd like to think he's a friend of mine and he's helped me very much.

00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:08.540
Joe Rickert runs the R views blog, which I highly recommend.

00:19:08.540 --> 00:19:14.599
And in this blog, he actually talked about survival analysis using R and is a great primer

00:19:14.599 --> 00:19:19.319
to take the simple code that we did and that data and use survival analysis and apply to

00:19:19.319 --> 00:19:20.319
it.

00:19:20.319 --> 00:19:26.800
So go to the R meetups, meet people, interact with everybody, and new ideas will come out

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:31.119
of it and make all of us better.

